      {
        "paragraph_index": 3,
        "text": "Monotonicity: Yes — K1 > K2 > K3 > K4. The steady decrease indicates negative cooperativity and site saturation: each added NH3 binds less strongly as the first, second, and third sites are filled. The fact that four stepwise bindings are all favorable yet progressively weaker is consistent with Cu(II)’s characteristic 4+2 (Jahn–Teller–elongated octahedral) preference: four strong equatorial NH3 donors form readily (approaching a square-planar equatorial set), while any 5th/6th donors are much weaker (axial, elongated).",
